 that led to almost 350 Mafia members being sent to prison.</p>
<p>

Buscetta revealed the existence and workings of the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../659/6294659.xml">
Sicilian Mafia Commission</link>. It enabled Falcone to argue that <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../869/361869.xml">
Cosa Nostra</link></it> was a unified hierarchical structure ruled by a Commission, and that its leaders – who normally would not dirty their hands with criminal acts – could be held responsible for criminal activities that were committed to benefit the organization. This premise became known as the Buscetta theorem and would be recognised legally with the confirmation of the Maxi Trial sentence in January 1992.</p>
<p>

His testimony in the <region wordnetid="108630985" confidence="0.8">
